I agree that in a general case Docker has benefits even for the resources.

I wanted to say that for this specific case, a WP site, your are using more RAM than WP itself.

I don't mean to say that Docker is generally bad.

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: I meant something like that if a program allocates 30MB, the memory allocated by that program and Docker is more than 30MB

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: That's more or less the same setup, except that you have to tunnel the traffic from the public IP to the Docker containet. It's not so hard and there's a lot of documentation üëçüèª

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet:
For example if a ransomware breaks into your wordpress site, you can simply delete that instance and create a new one.

With Docker it's possible to "load" directories in "read only" mode.

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: Cons is that you are using more resources that want you need (more or less). Pros is that if someone breaks into your docker, it can't hurt your system (precautions taken).

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: That's a hard question. What I know is that there is not difference between searching for tweets and scrolling down the page, and scraping tweets with Twint. The only automated feature is pressing "down" for a while, which is like placing tape on your keyboard

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: And with manually I mean with your web browser surfing on Twitter, no add-ons, pluings, anything.

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: With some code, you could manually scroll down the search page till the end, save the page and play with Twint offline, nothing would change

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: All in my opinion

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: Let's define "automated process" first. To search for tweets you place a keyword, to scrape tweets you set that same keyword. To set a specific date interval you set that interval, the same for Twint. What you do in twitter adv search you do in Twint as well. Where is automation?

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: And Twitter does not allow automated scraping processes. But Twint does no more automated processes than scrolling down the page.

name: Francesco Poldi
tweet: To summarize the answer, Twint does the same job that you would do with the web browser, search for tweets and see them, in the exactly same way
